{
  "doc_id": "6766",
  "text": "SAA is also the precursor of amyloid A protein, a fibrillar, insoluble product deposited in major organs, which carries a risk of organ failure and premature death in the course of secondary amyloidosis. AA amyloidosis is a late complication of RA, connected with active, long-standing, and disabling disease. The prevalence of AA amyloidosis in RA reported in different studies is highly variable because the complication frequently remains undetected due to lack of clinical manifestations in many patients [CITATION_1] . Persistently high concentration of SAA is a prerequisite for AA amyloidogenesis [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . High levels of SAA correlate with the progression of amyloidosis and low levels are associated with its regression [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . It was reported that, in AA amyloidosis patients, serum SAA concentration was the most important predictive parameter of the risk of death, associated with renal function [CITATION_6] .",
